  "prompt": "What are movies that everyone should see?",
  "response": "Okay, compiling a list of movies \"everyone should see\" is tough because taste is so subjective! But, I'll aim for a list that balances critical acclaim, cultural impact, historical significance, and a variety of genres.  I'll break it down into categories to make it a bit more digestible.\n\n**Classics & Foundational Films:**\n\n*   **Citizen Kane (1941):**  Often cited as the greatest film ever made. Groundbreaking in its storytelling and technical innovation.\n*   **Casablanca (1942):**  A timeless romance set against the backdrop of World War II.  Full of iconic lines and unforgettable characters.\n*   **The Godfather (1972):**  A masterpiece of crime cinema.  Explores themes of family, power, and corruption.\n*   **2001: A Space Odyssey (1968):** A visually stunning and thought-provoking science fiction film that explores the nature of humanity and its place in the universe.\n*   **Singin' in the Rain (1952):** A joyful and technically brilliant musical that celebrates the magic of Hollywood.\n*   **Lawrence of Arabia (1962):** A sweeping epic with stunning visuals and a complex character study.\n*   **Psycho (1960):** A masterclass in suspense and a landmark in the horror genre.\n*   **Bicycle Thieves (1948):** An Italian neorealist film that is a poignant and heartbreaking story of poverty and desperation.\n\n**Modern Classics & Culturally Significant:**\n\n*   **Pulp Fiction (1994):** A game-changing film that redefined independent cinema with its nonlinear narrative and memorable dialogue.\n*   **Schindler's List (1993):** A powerful and harrowing depiction of the Holocaust.\n*   **The Shawshank Redemption (1994):**  An inspiring story of hope and resilience in the face of adversity.\n*   **Forrest Gump (1994):** A feel-good film that captures the spirit of America in the second half of the 20th century.\n*   **Fight Club (1999):** A darkly comic and subversive film that explores themes of consumerism and alienation.\n*   **The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring (2001):** A groundbreaking fantasy film that brought J.R.R. Tolkien's world to life.\n*   **Spirited Away (2001):** A masterpiece of animation from Studio Ghibli, filled with imagination and wonder.\n*   **Inception (2010):** A mind-bending thriller that explores the nature of dreams and reality.\n*   **Parasite (2019):** A darkly comedic thriller that explores themes of class inequality and social commentary.\n*   **Everything Everywhere All at Once (2022):** A chaotic and heartfelt film that combines action, comedy, and sci-fi to explore themes of family, identity, and purpose.\n\n**Important & Thought-Provoking:**\n\n*   **To Kill a Mockingbird (1962):** A powerful and moving adaptation of Harper Lee's novel about racial injustice in the American South.\n*   **One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest (1975):** A tragicomic story about rebellion and conformity in a mental institution.\n*   **Do the Right Thing (1989):** A Spike Lee film that explores racial tensions in a Brooklyn neighborhood on a hot summer day.\n*   **Malcolm X (1992):** An epic biopic of the controversial African-American activist.\n*   **12 Years a Slave (2013):** A harrowing and important historical drama about slavery in the United States.\n*   **Spotlight (2015):** A gripping drama about the Boston Globe's investigation into the Catholic Church sex abuse scandal.\n\n**Genre Essentials (A Few Examples):**\n\n*   **Sci-Fi:** *Blade Runner (1982), Alien (1979), Arrival (2016)*\n*   **Comedy:** *Some Like It Hot (1959), Monty Python and the Holy Grail (1975), The Princess Bride (1987)*\n*   **Horror:** *The Exorcist (1973), The Shining (1980), Get Out (2017)*\n*   **Action:** *Die Hard (1988), The Matrix (1999), Mad Max: Fury Road (2015)*\n*   **Drama:** *The Social Network (2010), Moonlight (2016), Manchester by the Sea (2016)*\n*   **Animated:** *Toy Story (1995), The Lion King (1994), Wall-E (2008)*\n*   **Documentary:** *Man with a Movie Camera (1929), The Act of Killing (2012), Free Solo (2018)*\n\n**Important Considerations When Choosing:**\n\n*   **Your Personal Interests:** What genres do you enjoy? What topics interest you? Start there!\n*   **Cultural Context:**  Understanding the historical and social context of a film can greatly enhance your appreciation of it.\n*   **Accessibility:**  Many of these films are available on streaming services, for rent, or at your local library.\n*   **Don't Be Afraid to Disagree:** Just because a film is critically acclaimed doesn't mean you have to love it.  Form your own opinions!\n\n**How to Use This List:**\n\n*   **Don't try to watch them all at once!**  This is a lifetime of movie-watching.\n*   **Pick a category or two that interests you and start there.**\n*   **Read reviews and watch trailers** to get a better sense of what a film is about.\n*   **Talk to friends and family** about their favorite movies and get recommendations.\n\nThis list is just a starting point. There are countless other amazing movies out there waiting to be discovered. Happy watching!\n",
